{"parse":{"title":"The Jesus Factor","pageid":17136823,"revid":847023559,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption style=\"font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;\">The Jesus Factor <span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Jesus+Factor&amp;rft.author=%5B%5BEdwin+Corley%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=Stein+%26+Day+Paperback&amp;rft.pages=320\"></span></caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Jesus_factor_book.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Jesus factor book.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/a/ac/Jesus_factor_book.jpg\" width=\"184\" height=\"274\" data-file-width=\"184\" data-file-height=\"274\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Author</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Edwin_Corley\" title=\"Edwin Corley\">Edwin Corley</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Language</th><td>\nEnglish</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Genre</th><td>\nContemporary Fiction</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Publisher</th><td>\nStein &amp; Day Paperback</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><div style=\"padding:0.1em 0;line-height:1.2em;\">Published&#160;in English</div></th><td>\n1970</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Pages</th><td>\n320</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a></th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0812881042\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0812881042\">978-0812881042</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>The Jesus Factor</b></i> is a 1970 <a href=\"/wiki/Conspiracy_theory\" title=\"Conspiracy theory\">conspiracy theory</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Thriller_(genre)\" title=\"Thriller (genre)\">thriller</a> novel by <a href=\"/wiki/Edwin_Corley\" title=\"Edwin Corley\">Edwin Corley</a> based on the <a href=\"/wiki/Manhattan_Project\" title=\"Manhattan Project\">Manhattan Project</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II</a> and the bombing of <a href=\"/wiki/Hiroshima\" title=\"Hiroshima\">Hiroshima</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Nagasaki,_Nagasaki\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nagasaki, Nagasaki\">Nagasaki</a>. It concerns issues relating to the \"<a href=\"/wiki/Arms_race\" title=\"Arms race\">arms race</a>\" and the collective guilt of those involved with the bombings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Its fictional premise is the discovery during the development of <a href=\"/wiki/Nuclear_weapon\" title=\"Nuclear weapon\">nuclear weapons</a> that only detonate if stationary in a <a href=\"/wiki/Gravitational_field\" title=\"Gravitational field\">gravitational field</a>, making their use as air-dropped bombs impossible. In the novel, the nuclear attacks of <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II</a> are simulated using aeroplane-mounted <a href=\"/wiki/Magnesium\" title=\"Magnesium\">magnesium</a> flares and dispersed <a href=\"/wiki/Radionuclide\" title=\"Radionuclide\">radionuclides</a>, taking advantage of the destruction caused by an <a href=\"/wiki/Earthquake\" title=\"Earthquake\">earthquake</a>. An international conspiracy hides this fact in the interest of maintaining <a href=\"/wiki/Nuclear_deterrent\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nuclear deterrent\">nuclear deterrence</a>.\n</p><p>The story concerns events when this status quo is threatened by one of the original <a href=\"/wiki/Bombardier_(air_force)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bombardier (air force)\">bombardiers</a>, who discovers the conspiracy while running for US president with a policy of <a href=\"/wiki/Nuclear_disarmament\" title=\"Nuclear disarmament\">nuclear disarmament</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Jesus_Factor&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>The Novels of World War II: An Annotated Bibliography</i>, Desmond Taylor and Philip E. Hager, Garland, 1993, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0824056841\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0824056841\">0824056841</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20100528171439/http://www.wsu.edu/~brians/nuclear/c.htm\">Nuclear Holocausts Bibliography: C</a>, <i>Nuclear Holocausts: Atomic War in Fiction</i>, Paul Brians, Professor of English, Washington State University, Pullman, Washington (retrieved 3 July 2008).</li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Thrillerbook.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Thrillerbook.png/45px-Thrillerbook.png\" width=\"45\" height=\"45\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Thrillerbook.png/68px-Thrillerbook.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Thrillerbook.png/90px-Thrillerbook.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"128\" data-file-height=\"128\" /></a></td><td><i>This article about a <a href=\"/wiki/Thriller_novel\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Thriller novel\">thriller novel</a> of the 1970s is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//e